<h2>4. Bees</h2>

<p>With the lack of flowers for food, and the coming cold, bees hibernate through winter and emerge in Spring. There are many different types of bees, and not all are part of a hive, in fact 90% are solitary.</p>

<p>Each bee species hibernates but will wake up at different times depending on when their preferred nectar source blooms. Bumblebees are hive insects, with only the queen bee surviving the winter. One of its food sources are blossoms, especially willow, crab apple and hawthorn trees, so you&rsquo;re not the only one looking out for spring blossoms.</p>

<p>You can help solitary bees by providing them with a  <a href="https://www.rspb.org.uk/helping-nature/what-you-can-do/activities/build-a-bee-hotel">bee hotel</a>, a place to lay the next generation of bees. </p>
<p>The <a href="https://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/blog/2022/11/where-do-bees-go-in-winter/">woodland trust </a> has information about how to help bees, including planting bee friendly plants to help them survive through winter.</p>


